Author: kusoro
Content:
ill prolly be busy the next few hours so ill preemptively write a few hints for the beeg line sudoku i posted in case anyone ends up needing them
the first spoiler in each line will just point you to the relevant rule/some trivial observation, the next one, if its not the last, will point you towards some maybe less obvious observation, the last will ask the relevant question

getting the board
1. ||the boxes youre going to get cannot overlap||, ||almost the full grid is filled by the line||, ||can you have empty tiles (as in without a segment of the line) in your boxes?||
2. ||you have an 11x11 grid you need to fit 9 9x9 non-overlapping boxes into||, ||you can "remove" up to 2 rows/columns and still be able to fit 9 such boxes in||, ||which rows/columns will effectively force you to remove 3 rows/columns if removed, and what are their intersections?||
3. ||the segments of the line cut by the boundaries of the box must add up to the same number||, ||the sum of all the digits in the box is 45||, ||what are the factors of 45 and therefore how many segments of the line must every box contain?||

solving the board
1. ||normal sudoku rules apply||, ||you have boxes where two rows/columns have 9 spaces to fill in, while on one side the other row/column has only 6 spaces to fill in and on the other side the fourth row/column has 3 spaces to fill in||, ||how do those 6 and 3 spaces correspond?||
2. ||normal sudoku rules apply||, ||sometimes you have a situation similar to the one in hint 1, but you have 3 spaces on one side and 9 spaces on the other side, where the 3 spaces are filled in by a fourth box||, ||what can you say about those 3 spaces, and the 3 spaces on the other side?||

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: Next step should be (big spoiler): ||the 24 cage in box 9 has to be real, or else the math doesn't work on making the box add up to 45. So knowing that's real, you have to put 789 in it or else you can't make 24. One of the other cages in Box 9 has to be a coordinate one. If it's the 14 cage, then cell 1,4 has to be a 9. If it's the 12 cage then cell 1,2 has to be a 7. Either way that means there's a 7 or a 9 in row one OUTSIDE of the 16 cage in Box 3. Which means...||

Author: sentienceproblem
Content: ||It can be interesting to ask a question of how to reproduce the deduction without the set operations. In theory, you could ask yourself "is there a digit that cannot appear twice on diagonals?", and try to place 9 on r3c3 or similar (trivially the only candidates other than box 5), and then after 3/4 digits see that it's contradictory. The problem with "set theory" solutions is they look more like magic than they actually are & it's fun to bring them "down" to earth like that.||

Author: cjlj
Content: Rules:  Consider the first X cells and the last Y cells of a row or column where X is the number in the first cell and Y is the number in the last cell. A clue outside the grid gives the sum of the digits where these groups overlap, or the sum of the digits in the gap between the groups if they don't overlap. A cell is colored red if it's part of an overlap in its row AND in its column. It's green if it's part of a gap in its row AND in its column. In this puzzle all clues are encrypted: each letter from A-J must be paired with a number from 0-9. Different letters are different numbers.  Digits in cages must sum to the clue in the top left of a cage. The number AB represent the number for which A is the tens digit, and B the units. It does not means A*B.

Content: https://logic-masters.de/Dateien/bild.php?data=d90b59ec-22493-31363732392d32

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: Isn't this broken?

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: Everything works except for the orange line.

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: The 4 above the 3 doesn't have a valid value to be 2 different than the 3, or am I missing something?

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: It's only used on the orange line constraint twice so it has to be 4 and 2 value.

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: This is a mindfuck of a ruleset btw. It's cool but I'm pretty daunted about trying it.

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: Oh are you allowed to use any value of a factor of 2? It you don't have to use them all to get from the true value to the lowest?

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: If so then this isn't broken.

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: Like I could have an 8 in a cage. Then one more 8 in another cage somewhere else that I can value at 1. And those are the only two 8s I ever put in cages?

Author: joseph_anderson_
Content: I don't have to put four 8s in cages to get from 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1?

Author: vikingprime_
Content: You would be correct with the second example, if it has been used once it can be reduced by any factor of 2

Author: vikingprime_
Content: So in the above example valid options for 4 after being used *as* a 4 would be 1, or 2, or 2 and 1

Author: vikingprime_
Content: You could have: an 8 -> 4 -> 1; or an 8 -> 2 -> 1; or an 8 ->1; or 8 -> 4 -> 2;  or an 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1

Content: and may I say, you checking out the puzzle is one of the cooler moments of my life. I'll just be over here, quietly soaking it in

Author: iceninja
Content: If you're using an app that randomly generates them,  then they're usually run through a sudoku solver that limits itself to non-straight-up-brute-force techniques. If it fails that the puzzle would be discarded (or sometimes the puzzles are directly  generated from a solve path}, so you can probably trust that any given puzzle there is  solvable without just trying every combination (at least if the app isn't some amateur implementation)

Author: bad_fetus
Content:
I can see a slightly convoluted way to ||eliminate 9 from the highlighted cell:

1. If it's 9, you get a 1234 quadruplet in col 8, forcing a 5 in r6c8 

2. that forces a 248 triple in r6 box 4

3. that forces a 1 in r5c1 (important)

4. r4c3 is forced to be a 5 per above, which then forces r4c6 to be a 2 (important)

5.  steps 4 and 3 together are impossible as 1 and 2 are both eliminated from r5c4 now.

Meaning r4c8 cannot be a 9. 
||

Author: iceninja
Content:
Spoilers for sudon'tku !!!!!

||  The break-in with the suspicously long thermo is very cool, but i started to enjoy the puzzle even more once it became about finishing each set of numbers.  

There's so many points where you logic leads you into a cage that lets you suddenly elimnate things,  very satisfying use of cages... always feels like the setter is one step ahead of your logic path ready to give you a helpful cage.

The way the sixes get placed is super cool, that's definetly a highlight.  The middle sixes you realize have to be all in a column because of the other two, the logic for the 21 cage of sixes is neat and feels like it breaks a lot open, and the left column of sixes is part of the break-in chain.    I was expecting those sixes to be there because otherwise the kropki dot wouldn't be relevant, so that was a good hint to figure out why they had to be there.  

Had to rollback a mistake with ones at one point in this puzzle, it's easy to get yourself mixed up on how the thermos must work

Also lol at the 2 cell  20 cages
The end of the puzzle was really long for me, it took me a while to figure out how to disambuigate 4,6,7 and 8 (plus two possible 9 configurations)||

Author: vikingprime_
Content: It's like a more flexible renban

Author: vikingprime_
Content: and in some ways less, but essentially every subsequent digit has the same difference (e.g. a "4" Same Difference line could go "1-5-9" and then be forced to stop, unless it has the opportunity to find another 1/5/9 in another box; a "3" same difference line could be "1-4-7" or "2-5-8" etc)

Author: vikingprime_
Content: It could be "1" difference and become like a Renban, but adjacent digits would have to be sequential

Author: bad_fetus
Content: _usually_ the problem comes down to explaining the common variant rules: If you don't summarise them it's annoying to the regulars and otherwise it's difficult (but still understandable) for the newbies

Author: bad_fetus
Content: on occasion unique new rules have the problem of being opaque to both newcomers and regulars but it's not too common even sitting in the sudoku servers in my experience - the above problem happens often either way but it's unavoidable

Author: bad_fetus
Content: as a very generic example, most puzzles start with "normal sudoku rules apply.". This is already poor if you're not familiar with the basic sudoku rules

Author: bad_fetus
Content: at the same time, obviously, you don't need to read what those are as a regular

Author: bad_fetus
Content: a lot of the common variant rules have that same problem, the setter ultimately has to pick one of the two "evils"

Author: vikingprime_
Content:
Thank you! Are you referring to the same style of puzzle as well? or specifically around the same challenge level? 

My favourite puzzle I think I've made is a liar puzzle called "What Lies Beyond the Fog": https://logic-masters.de/Raetselportal/Raetsel/zeigen.php?id=000G9A 
It's more challenging but it's also a Fog puzzle, which helps balance out the challenge by limiting the scope of where to look. 

For something of a similar challenge level but different rules, "Wavy Zippers" is a fun one and comes with the Marty Sears stamp-of-approval (he's been featured on the channel quite a bit, really great setter): https://logic-masters.de/Raetselportal/Raetsel/zeigen.php?id=000G8S
